metadata.name: Obliques #187
metadata.description:
Obliques are a reinterpretation of Parallels, a collection of AI generated color fields by Marc Maurer. Many of the pieces in that collection are CC0, which basically means they can be reused for other projects, like this one.

Obliques takes artifacts from Parallels and uses them as brushes, painting slices of the original image on the canvas in a (hopefully) pleasant, chaotic way.

About 10% will be "Glitched".

The "Source Material" property will tell you the name of piece that it is using.

You can see Marc Maurer's Parallels project here:
https://objkt.com/collection/KT1TiSEcASGD19SW8bmqrqgSgCBkwXqDdTJ1

Obliques are also CC0, so feel free use anything here in other projects.

You can read more about CC0 here:
https://creativecommons.org/share-your-work/public-domain/cc0/

G : Toggle Grain
M : Toggle Matte
S : Save Image
1 -> 6 : Set pixel density
(Default pixel density is 1 @ 2000x2000)

metadata.name: Imperium #671
metadata.description:
Imperium is a study of shapes and colors, and how a very small set of shapes and colors, when given equally simple rules, can create a great variety of patterns that may bring meaning to the viewer.

Press the s key for a quick download at the current resolution, and press the space bar to display the export and information menu.

For more information, read the collection guide:
https://medium.com/@MrMallory/imperium-the-collection-guide-cd9ab7e05aa0

metadata.name: Drifters #13
metadata.description:
In an undiscovered area, you've stumbled upon an unknown creature.
It looks weirdly haunting, and you're feeling a sense of unease.

You're wondering what it's doing.

It seems to move in patterns, and sometimes suddenly changes course.
Is it communicating?

(to whom?)

Setting aside your discomfort for a moment, you're realizing you could be seeing it wrong.
While the creature does look eerie and its motivations are unclear,
you realize every culture has its own appreciation of aesthetics,
and you can't help noticing there is a certain grace to this performance.

And it all makes sense.

You're witnessing uncharted explorations of elegance.

–

Append [?scale=<number>] to the url to scale the renderer.
Press [control / command + s] to save the current frame to a file.

© 2022 Monokai.

metadata.name: Mur #280
metadata.description:
Mur is a series of computational drawings of stacked and falling bricks. The bricks are placed in different configurations of walls, towers, stacks and paths, and are then exposed to gravity. 

The graphics are coded with p5.js and the rigid body simulations with ammo.js. In live mode, press 's' to save a screenshot and 'e' to save a high resolution image. Press 't' to toggle textures. 

Each scene is drawn twice, first brick by brick as they fall or stay in place, then the scene as a whole. Mur is optimized for Chrome, uses WebGL and may not work in all browsers.

metadata.name: Aliens #74
metadata.description:
"Aliens" is a collection derivated from "The Odd One Out" collection where you can see up close one of these some of its aliens:
- Longlorb: A slug-alien, not the most intelligent
- Skidle: A big mouth alien
- Trunglute: A mutated tree-alien
- Penclope: A cyclope alien with five tentacles
- NFT-Rex: An alien that may come from the dinoverse
- Blurp: An alien that will eat everything
- Booz: The main protagonist of the crowd, the one that needs to be find out

---------- CONTROLS -----------
- Double-click on the token to zoom into the picture (on Smartphone you can zoom normally)
- Right-click on the token to trigger download options (4 download options are available, low-res, normal-res, high-res and SVG), if you want to download a very high-fidelity of your token, I recommend the SVG option (Which you can then convert into PNG on various websites).

metadata.name: Pencil Lines #33
metadata.description:
This project is a journey to embrace creativity with a programmatic form. As a child, I carried a pencil and paper to mimic the world around me. The paper canvas provided a path to empathize with a world, so I could attempt to better understand it. At some point along the way, I lost touch with the analog medium and found myself taken with the structure of computers and languages. Over time, computers became more of a consumption engine. Almost a year ago, I started on a daily journey of returning to creation with the p5js medium. Today marks my 306th day of that journey. Each day the canvas and I practice what can be. Each day beauty is found and destroyed.

This canvas is generated by varied line strokes and gaps in between. As my practice evolved, patterns began to appear. I watched as the canvas transformed into woven fabric and at other times pencil shading practices. The forms were magical and captivating and thus are both part of this project.

Wishing this project offers as much joy to others as it did for me.

metadata.name: Sprawling Walls #27
metadata.description:
I recall living for quite some time in urban village areas, where they formed within a striking urban setting. Unlike suburban houses where spaces are ample and most housings are planned with careful consideration of other houses, these urban villages are limited by site and geographic boundaries. So it's almost inevitable that houses are built so close with each other, so much that no house has a backyard or front yard, everything was just roof and walls as far as the eye can see. Because these dwellings grow persistently according to the wants and needs of their dwellers, as the families within these walls grow, so does the urban village.

It's a chaotic scene for sure, but urban villages have their own candid beauty. Just by looking from the stacked facades of the walls that made up the houses, we can imagine the warm dynamic between the people and strong living impulses that spark from behind these walls.
